	                Proving: For all integers $m$, $n$, and $p$ if $m+n+p$ is even, then either 1 or 3 of the numbers must be even\\
	                \underline{Proof by contrapositive:}\\
	                Contrapositive: For all integers $m$, $n$, and $p$, if 2 of the numbers are even then $m+n+p$ is odd \\
	                Definition of an even number: $\exists _{k \in \mathbb{Z}} \text{ s.t. } n=2k$ \\
