	I think the main difference between Zeus in Prometheus Bound and Hesiod's
	Theogony is his leadership styles. In Hesiod's Theogony Zeus is much more of
	a teamwork first leader and in Prometheus Bound it seems he is acting a bit
	harsher and more in command. I think this can first be seen in the beginning
	when Kratos, Via, and Hephaistos are chaining Prometheus to the mountain.
	"Hephaistos: It’s a heavy thing this, to be a friend and a relative. Kratos:
	Sure, but is it proper to disobey your father’s word? Aren’t you more afraid of
	that?" (Aeschylus, 30). In this dialogue Hephaistos and Kratos are both in
	agreement that it is hard to chain your friend to a mountain but are too scared
	of Zeus to not do so. This clearly shows Zeus is much harsher and enforcing his
	demands. In a later statement, the Chorus says, "This is because new gods rule
	the heavens now, Prometheus and Zeus, who is now the harsher ruler has replaced
	the old laws with new ones and he has trampled upon the old powers" (Aeschylus,
	130). Here is another demonstration of Zeus's power and harsh rule. I think the
	main difference for this can be found when taking a look at the current
