	                \underline{Expansion of recurrence relation:}\\
	                $T(N) = 3T(N/2)+1\\$
	                $= 3T(N/4)+1+1\\$
	                $= 3T(N/8)+1+1+1\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $=T(N/N) +$ . . . $+ 1+1+1\\$
	                With each recursive call the size of $N$ is being divided by 2 which is a logarithmic pattern. It gets multiplied by $3$ which is a constant so it gets dropped leaving us with $O(logN)$
	            \item[(e)]
	                $O(log(N))\\$
	                \underline{Expansion of recurrence relation:}\\
	                $T(N) = T(N/4)+1\\$
	                $= T(N/16)+1+1\\$
	                $= T(N/64)+1+1+1\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $\cdot\\$
	                $=T(N/N) +$ . . . $+ 1+1+1\\$
	                With each recursive call the size of $N$ is being divided by 4 which is a logarithmic pattern. This give the complexity of $O(log_{4}N)$ which is simplified to $O(logN)$
