	    This reading presents many ideas that in modern day would be faced with harsh criticism. Throughout the beginning of the story when Demeter loses her daughter, she isn't offerend help from many of the people that heard her daughter's cry. When she finally does get help from the son of Hyperion he says "you should not have an anger without bounds, all in vain. It is not unseemly to have, of all the immortals, such a son-in-law as Hādēs" (Homer, 75). This comment here says that it's not such a big deal that Zeus gave her daughter away to Hades soleley because her son-in-law is now Hades which is a really good thing. It really devalues Persophone and makes it seem like her husband being someone of power is better than someone who she chooses. "she was  wasting  away  with  yearning  for  her  daughter  with  the  low-slung waistband. 305 She made that year the most terrible one for mortals" (Homer, 350). In this line here it connects the distress and sadness of demeter with bad weather and a terrible year for the people on earth. Demeter has had seomthing happend to her daughter that would make anyone distraught, and yet this story treats it like it's no big deal and that she shouldn't really be sad. Overall it really makes it seem as if women were second to men in Greek society. What Demeter or Persophone wanted was always given second priority to what ever Zeus or Hādēs wanted. Women were very likely not given much responsibiltiy or rights in ancient Greek Society.
