	                    \underline{Bubble sort}
	                        Yes, bubble sort is stable. Bubble sort will iterate over an array of items linearly and only swap if the second element is less than the first element. If both are the same nothing will be done, and there is no way for an element to get behind another unless it is less than, not equal to it since at most elements move 1 spot at a time. This quality means that two same elements will be in the same order in the unsorted and sorted array making it stable.
	                \item[(b)]
	                    \underline{Selection sort}
	                        No, selection sort is not stable. Swaps that occur can be jumps of $1$ spots all the way to $n-1$ spots. In these large jumps it's possible for the element to jump over one that is equal to it meaning that two equal values may end up in different spots making it not stable.
	                \item[(c)]
	                    \underline{Insertion sort}
	                        Yes, insertion sort is stable. Insertion sort will iterate over an array in it's unsorted order and add them to the "sorted" side of the array. With each new element it will then iterate backwards (descending) order over the sorted section to find where it belongs. When it encounters an element that it is equal to it will not swap. Since this is the case, an element that is first in unsorted order will be added to the "sorted" side first and any same element will be added after and placed after.
	                \item[(d)]
	                    \underline{Shellsort}
	                        No, shellsort is not stable. Elements of the same value can end up in different orders from their unsorted start. If a value, say $4$ is the 5th element in an unsorted array, and there is also a $4$ in the 4th spot, the $4$ in the 5th spot will appear first in the sorted array if shell sort is using groups of every 4th element. When doing the groupings it does not look at numbers that are in between so based on the groups it could easily swap two elements that are of the same value as I showed in the example making it not stable.
	                    
