	One of the main takeaways from this reading is how much the gods seem to use the mortals in complete disregard for their thoughts and feelings. Aphrodite has slept with Anchises and then goes on to expain how he must never tell another person and really how embarrased she is of it. "I have gone very far off the track, in a wretched and inexcusable way. I have  strayed  from  my  noos.  255  I  got  myself  a  child  beneath  my  waistband, having slept with a male mortal" (Sappho 224). The descriptive words Aphrodite uses to describe the act she commited tells us everything about how she feels about mortals. She calls it wretched and inexcusable what she has done so clearly she has no respect for mortals. "But if you say out loud and boast, with a thūmos bereft of phrenes, that you made love [philotēs] to the Lady of Cythera, the one with the beautiful garlands, then Zeus in his anger will smite you with a  smoking  thunderbolt" (Sappho 289). Aphrodite has used Anchises for her own personal desires and is now forcing the mortals to keep it a secret. She just does what she wants and then makes demands that mortals must follow or be striked down by Zeus. This is incredibly selfish. The sad part is the mortals are in no position to do anything about it. Aphrodite has the power of Zeus on her side and no one is going to try and stand up against that. It's interesting because this is so different from any kind of modern religion where the god(s) are respected and loved and the god(s) are loving towards mortals.
