	Part 1
	
	1. My algorithm iterates over the array with a for loop and within that loop there is a while loop. The while loop iterates while the value in front of the current one is greater than or equal to the initial value from the for loop. It then records when the while loop condition is not true and there we have the start and end of a sub array. The runtime of this portion if O(n). It does a single iteration over the list.
	
	2. A 2d array holds the data for the sub arrays. Each element in the array is an array of length 2 where the first element is the start of the sub array and the second is the end. The algorithm iterates over that data structure and merges sub arrays that are next to each other however it will not wrap around (merge the last sub array and first). Using an array to manage the sub arrays in the very worst case adds O(n) time and that would be if there are no sub arrays and the list is descending.
	
	3. In the very best case the array is already sorted and it takes a total of O(n) time. When the algorithm gets the sub arrays it does one iteration of the list and finds 1 sub array. Then, in the main sort methods the first while loop never runs because the condition is while (pairs.length > 1) and the length would be just 1 since there is 1 pair for the single sub array.
	
	In the very worst case the array is strictly descending and there are no sub arrays greater than size 1. It would take O(n) time to get the pairs and then the run time to get all of those sorted would be O(nlogn) because this is basically the point in a typical merge sort algorithm where it gets to the bottom of the recursion right before merging.
	
	4. This algorithm is better than merge sort in everything but the worst case where it would be similar. Merge sort starts by breaking up the array into smaller and smaller pieces until its just two elements and it compares them and works its way up. In this algorithm, there is already chunks that are sorted and we know this. Say there are 3 sub arrays of length 4. My algorithm here can start right away merging the sub arrays of size 4 where merge sort will separate and go down until you have arrays of size 2 and see that they are already sorted which is wasted time.
	
	Part 2
	1. In the worst case this quicksort algorithm runs in O((2n-2)^2) or simplified as O(n^2). This would happen when pivot 1 is at the first index and pivot 2 is at the last index every single time.This would require pivot 1 to check all elements up until pivot 2 and pivot 2 to check all elements before pivot 1. The best case is O(nlogn). This is the case when the pivots end up next to each other as it produces the same result as standard quicksort
	
	2. It can definitely depend on the situation for which one is better, but I think overall 3 way quicksort is best. Reason for this is when creating the 2 pivot points in 5 way, you end up comparing elements twice. All the elements that are greater than pivot 1 but less than pivot 2 have to be looked at twice which makes for a worse run time. 5 way can be better as with 3 way you can end up with n^2 time if your pivot is at either the first spot or last spot of the array for each pivot. With 5 way this is still possible, but the odds are much lower of both pivots being at the extremes. This is rather rare, and so for most cases 3 way is best
	
	Part 3
	
	1. Removing from the priority queue first requires finding the location of the patient in the queue and ususing a standard search it would take O(logn) time. Using the hash map we are able to find the patient object in constant time and in the patient object is the location of the patient in the priority queue. Then removing that from the queue and reorganizing it takes O(logn) time.
	
	For update, the process is the same for locating the position of the patient in priority queue. We can find its location by getting the object from the hash map. Then the patient needs to find its new location which in the worst case can take O(logn) time since it could have to be moved all the way to the top or bottom from the opposite side.
	
	2.
	* Process
	    * this function performs some constant time operations in the start (incrementing processed, creating a new patient, comparing two numbers, sendToER()) followed by an O(logn) operation which is calling insert on the priority queue. Inserting a patient puts it at the bottom of the queue and swims it up. The swim function in the worst case is O(logn) as it is basically doing binary search up the queue and in the best case it is O(1) if the patient does not have to swim up the queue. Expected run time should be somewhere between the best and worse but closer to the worst case. It is likely that it will have to do some amount of swimming so expected is O(clogn) (c being a constant)
	
	* seeNext
	    * Everything called in this function is a constant operation except for delMax() which in the worst case is O(logn) and in the best case something less but still not constant time unless the queue size is 1. After the max is deleted, the top is replace with the bottom element in the queue which will always have some amount of sinking to do. Since it was at the bottom there are many elements of greater value ahead of it and this amount of sinking will vary but the expected case is still O(logn).
	
	* handle_emergency
	    * Everything performed in this function is of constant time except for the function call to setUrgency() which in the best case is O(1) and the worst case is O(logn). In the best case the urgency of the patient is changed but not enough to cause it to move up or down in the queue leaving it at constant time. In the worst case the patient starts out at the bottom of the queue and the urgency is changed to the max (or the opposite scenario). This would cause it to move across the entire array which is O(logn) time. For both the best and worst case the search for the element in the queue is O(1) since the patient object can be found in the hashmap and that stores the location in the queue. Expected should be something closer to the worst case since if there is a change to urgency there will be pretty large movement unless the patient was already of very high urgency.
	
	* walk_out
	    * This function has 2 constant time operations and then a function call to remove. The remove function has a best case runtime of O(1) and a worst case of O(logn). Searching for the element in the queue is O(1) since the location in the queue can be found through the hash map. Then in this best case, the element removed is the last element in the queue and nothing else needs to be moved. In the worst case, it is the top element which requires lots of sinking to get the queue back in order and gives the O(logn) time. The expected time is O(logn) as well. The best case is pretty rare and only happens when one of the last 2 items are removed so if anything else is removed there needs to be changes to the order which is O(logn).
