	            An example of when a hashtable would be most useful when keeping a record of people who have already used their free trial. Order doesn't matter here you simply need to quickly look up if they are in the hashtable which is O(1) time and if they aren't add them to it which is also O(1) time. Extra space is needed as in a typical hashtable the load factor is 1/2 so in the best case it would use O(n) space and worst case O(3n) which is just O(n). For a balanced search tree an example of where this could be useful is the same as the hashtable. Searching would be O(logn) every time as well as deleting and inserting require balancing which is O(clogn) where c is a constant and it although it reduces down to O(logn) it can be quite time consuming where as a hashtable is O(1) for inserting and deleting. Inserting into a hashmap can be O(n) when it needs to be rehashed however the amortized cost of doing so is still O(1).The main advantage of using a balanced tree over a hashtable is space. As mentioned before, a hashtable requires at least O(n) space whereas a tree is O(1) always. Both are fairly simple to program so there is not a big advantage to either in that regard.
