	To me a hero is someone that sets an example for others to follow and is always making decisions for the greater good of his or her people. A hero is never afraid to take the first step in to battle as he knows it's what will inspire his people. On top of this, a hero is also human. Meaning they make mistakes and have flaws. I think this is best represented in the beginning of the excerpt where Agamemnon sends his heralds to get Briseis "Achilles withdrew from his men, weeping, and sat by the shore of the grey sea, gazing at the shadowy deep; and stretching out his arms, passionately, prayed to his dear mother" (Homer). Here Achilles is doing something we all do as normal humans, and that's cry. The reason I think this is such an important trait for a hero is having a strong appeal to your followers is crucial. If you are some perfect hero who never messes up your followers will never aspire to be like you since you are perfect. If you as a hero show your flaws, this enables others to look at you as if you aren't that different and that they too maybe be like you. "With this, he rushed at the Trojans in godlike fury" (Homer). In this scene here Achilles shows another trait I hold valuable in a hero which is not being afraid to be the first in battle. Achilles is the type to not tell his people to do something he wouldn't. He's always taking charge and to me that is one of the most necessary parts of a hero.
