	After reading this excerpt of the Odyssey, I think I can confidently say that Odysseus is a greater hero than Achilles. I think Odysseus is a great leader and is more in touch with his people. He clearly is the more compassionate leader, and I think that can be shown here: "Circe, what decent man could bring himself to eat and drink before he had freed his men, and seen them face to face? If you wish me in truth to eat and drink as you ask, then set them free and let me see my loyal friends with my own eyes." (Homer). Odysseus is willing to battle stand up for just a few of his people where I think Achilles might not have cared as much. Even after receiving an oath from Circe's he wants to make sure they're ok. A way that they are similar is that they are very respected by their men "So we left the ship and shore, but Eurylochus did not stay behind by the hollow hull, he came with us, fearing my stern rebuke" (Homer). Here Eurylochus wants to stay behind but ultimately decides not to in order for Odysseus not to get mad at him. Another way that they are different is that I think Odysseus relies a little more on his thinking than on his physicalness. This does make sense as Achilles is nearly invincible but Odysseus seems to be more so focused on the strategy than Achilles. Lastly I think one more similarity is Their ability to lead and be an example. In last weeks response I touched on this and how being the one to first go into battle and never ask your people to do something you wouldn't is a huge trait of a hero to me and I think they both exeplify this really well.
